	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Improving information on food safety, SPS and quality-standard requirements</h1>

			
			<h4>
												03 April 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>In February 2011, the South African Bureau of Standards (SABS) and Department of Trade and Industry (DTI) launched an early warning system ‘[to] enable exporters to receive information about changes in the standards, regulations and technical specifications that are used by other countries’. The aim of the initiative is to ‘give South Africa’s export industry time to align its processes in order to comply with the requirements of trading partners’. The system works by exporters subscribing to a weekly email service which provides information on changes to standards, regulations and technical specifications drawn from obligatory WTO notifications. Such changes need to be lodged at least 60 days before the regulations are adopted.</p><p>Some 45% of the regulations implemented by WTO member countries related to ‘health and safety’ issues, although there is now a growing number of ‘notifications related to environmental standards’. It is maintained that the scheme will make it easier for South African exporters to ensure conformity with evolving SPS, food-safety and other regulatory requirements.</p><p>In addition, exporters have to adapt to the standards imposed by private firms (such as supermarkets). These are private and, sometimes, notionally ‘voluntary’ and therefore not included in government regulations. The International Trade Centre has launched an online tool ‘to facilitate access to information on private/voluntary standards and to increase opportunities for sustainable production and trade’. The tool, ‘Standards Map’, is the latest addition to a family of online trade databases (including TradeMap and MacMap) that are essential tools for market research and trade analysis. Users must register – but access is free to all subscribers based in a developing country.</p><p>Meanwhile, Ethiopia has introduced a new Environmental and Social regulation to improve the quality of horticultural production and ‘prevent the use of banned or unregistered chemicals whilst encouraging an environmentally friendly waste disposal system’. The grading system is based on a 3-tier system: gold, silver and bronze. The new regulations apply to the cultivation of flowers, vegetables and fruits.</p><p>Beyond the ACP, EU cooperation with Thailand is to be intensified to address SPS problems faced in the export of selected vegetables (see <i>Agritrade </i>article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Regions/EU" target="_blank">Food safety concerns bring temporary halt to Thai vegetable exports</a>’ March 2011), involving systematic pre-shipment inspections by the Thai authorities and the secondment of EU officials to help the Thai authorities with quality control. The Thai authorities have until January 2012 to meet all quality and SPS requirements in the affected sectors, otherwise Thai exporters will face more stringent EU measures, possibly including an import ban. Thai producers’ representatives however said they still had ‘no details of the EU requirements’, beyond being informed that ‘the produce should be completely free from insect contamination’.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
