<a href="http://www.bangkokpost.com/business/economics/224237/eu-gives-fruit-exporters-ultimatum" target="_self">http://www.bangkokpost.com/business/economics/224237/eu-gives-fruit-expo...</a>&nbsp;</p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The Thai case highlights the need for close cooperation between EU and national authorities in exporting countries to ensure that producers have a clear and detailed understanding of SPS, food-safety and quality standards, and that national authorities have a clear understanding of the inspection and control requirements. The Ethiopian case illustrates the need for aligning national legislation with requirements in major export markets, while the South African initiative highlights the need for constant attention to be paid to these issues in order to keep producers updated on market requirements.</p><p>Together, these three cases highlight the multi-dimensional nature of the challenge to be taken up and addressed through the SPS and food-safety cooperation provisions of the proposed EPAs. The SABS/DTI initiative highlights the scope for the use of information technology to better serve producer organisations involved in exporting. However it also highlights the need to extend such initiatives beyond monitoring of immediately pending regulations notified to the WTO, to include an analysis of the broad direction of regulatory changes in major overseas markets. This could provide a longer time-frame for private-sector companies to integrate necessary investments in meeting evolving SPS, food-safety and quality standards into their routine reinvestment plans (e.g. investments in cattle transporters designed to meet future animal-welfare standards). This, however, suggests a need for strategic dialogue within sector-specific bodies to promote better understanding of the forthcoming trends in major international markets.</p><p>Since this can be a costly exercise, such information networks may most cost-effectively be built up at the regional level, building on existing specialist agencies (e.g. the South African Bureau of Standards, which provides benchmark standards for much of southern Africa).</p><p>At the same time, as many agro-exporters have discovered, the standards that exporters must attain in order to sell into the most dynamic outlets may exceed those that are formally required by SPS regulations. The supermarkets have very stringent demands in terms of traceability, chemical residues, environmental and social certification and, of course, presentation and packaging. It is hard to compare the requirements in different market segments, but this is essential to avoid being locked into value chains that apply more expensive burdens (relative to prices received) than others. The Standards Map launched by International Trade Centre earlier this year may help to cut the costs incurred by exporters in making such comparisons.</p>
		</div>
		
